    "faq_eTjxYh": {
      "type": "faq",
      "blocks": {
        "text_P9fgLa": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What is Mad Honey?",
            "answer": "<p>Mad honey is the high-altitude wild honey prepared by the largest honebee species Apis laboriosa in the mountains of Nepal. It is harvested only twice a year. The limit in the availability is due to the seasonal blooms of alpine flowers, mainly rhododendrons.</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_ptGRKd": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What makes Nepal mad honey different?",
            "answer": "<p>Any honey reflects the environment it comes from and Nepal mad honey is different in carrying the imprint of remote Himalayan cliff hives, <em>Apis laboriosa</em> bees, seasonal rhododendron blooms and traditional honey-hunting.</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_JiV8Cy": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Is mad honey only found in Nepal?",
            "answer": "<p>No. Nepal and Turkey are the two countries associated with mad honey production. Nepal mad honey comes from the wild hives in the mountainous cliffs, while in Turkey, hives are intentionally set in the rhododendron forests of the Black Sea region.</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_nwBa8P": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What makes Nepal mad honey so valuable?",
            "answer": "<p>Nepal mad honey carries a premium price because it is gathered from wild Himalayan bee colonies rather than farm-managed hives. Harvesting happens only in limited seasons, often twice a year, and requires skilled collectors to reach remote mountain cliffs.</p><p>The rarity, traditional harvesting method, careful handling, and transportation from rugged Himalayan terrain all add to its value compared to regular honey</p><p>Compared to other types of honey, mad honey is naturally produced in the high cliffs of Nepal which is far from human habitation, collected from the altitude above 3500+ meters and has a darker, flowery wild profile and unique tastes.</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_U6DB8c": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Where does our Mad Honey come from?",
            "answer": "<p>Our mad honey is sourced from the Himalayan forests of Nepal where bees gather nectar from high-altitude alpine and sub-alpine flowers. Each jar comes with a barcode connected to harvest details and traceability records.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
